I don’t believe there are dumb or stupid questions.

Just higher-quality questions than others.

What do you think?

What we focus on EXPANDS.

Rather than focusing on…

what we don’t enjoy and or don’t want in our lives, we can choose a new focus. 

Focus that’s directed to a positive stated and ideal outcome we’re in search of. 

When we focus on something we want to obtain, experience, accomplish, do, create, and or share with the world, we get a vastly different emotional response to said focus. 

Emotions drive action and I like to view emotions as “energy in motion”. I’m confident some of you have probably heard that and can attest to how true it really is. 

With focus comes energy. That energy is how the body communicates: emotions. 

Those emotions either inspire us to act or they can paralyze us or prevent us from acting. 

The difference comes from our focus.

Just a reminder to those weathering the storm in whatever capacity the “storm” presents itself in your life. 

Pain, like discomfort, is inevitable. 

Pain and discomfort are often needed to redirect our focus to find what’s not working so we can course correct. 

What’s also cool about pain & discomfort is that they’re often temporary, if……

we choose to embrace them for what’s on the other side…..

Our ideal desired outcomes.

I like looking at pain and discomfort as signals of information or, a “North Star” of where to direct my focus to access what I want in life. 

Like any emotion or sensation in the body, they are signaling to us vital lessons we can choose to suppress and avoid, or we can embrace and look for the learnings. 

It’s not always easy by any means. 

I know what pain feels like on all levels of human experiences: 

- physical (seen above)
- mental (attributed to the latter)
- emotional (attributed to both physical and mental)
- well as spiritual. 

It’s a cyclical relationship we have with pain and discomfort as all 4 levels of human experience are impacted, which can and often do profoundly affect our performance. 

I’m thankful for what BMX & multiple brain tumors taught me: suffering is a choice. 

We can choose to avoid the signals form our mind and body, and stay in the known comfortable space of familiarly while experiencing continuous pain (suffering). 

Or….

We can choose to be couragous to face our fears of what we know needs to change to experience our ideal and desired life. 

It’s all about perspective. 

Much love to anyone facing rough times. 

I’ve been there. 

I’m there now (more to come on this). 

But, I know this storm shall pass and trust you’ll find a similar path for yourself.

“Excuses prevent greatness” is hung up at my gym. 

I feel this. 

It’s not to dismiss sh** in life happening outside of our control & sucking. 

It’s about becoming aware of the story we create about what happened that holds us back from overcoming whatever it is in front of us. 

Our left brain is “the interpreter” of our lives and helps craft a story of what’s going on in life, which inspires meaning we make and live by. 

The story is just a story but if we tell ourself that story for long enough, it gets embedded into our belief system as the code we operate by. 

Our code is what influences our behavior, habits, and patterns in life that create the results we experience. 

This is how we find ourselves in trouble wanting to change an aspect of our health, performance, career, etc.

It’s all a story that inspired action & results. 

If you’re unhappy with any aspect of your life:

1. Become aware of the story & how it’s not serving you.
2. Define what you ideally want to experience stated positively. 
3. Map out congruent actions, thoughts, people, and emotions you must participate in to experience your ideal outcome. 
4. Act in alignment with (#3) and stay focused. 

Are you aware of the story you have been telling yourself?

What’s the story?

I dropped out of high school to chase my dreams of becoming an X-Games athlete.

Here are 10 things I learned from becoming a pro BMX athlete as a young teenager:

Visualization: from when I was 13 (in this photo), I created a vision I could only see in my mind, and it is what inspired my every decision for the years to come.

Work ethic: the amount of time, energy, and sacrifice I put into BMX are unfathomable.
 
Persistence & Grit: nothing is handed to you in Action Sports.

Pushing boundaries leads to growth: We only realize our potential if we push ourselves into uncomfortable territory. 

Failure is a choice: I fell countless times over the years to learn one trick. That process taught me failure is a choice.

Adaptability: No contest was the same layout, and you had to be able to adapt quickly. Being able to adapt to new environments is what sets apart the pro's from the am's. 

Health Is Internal: I was diagnosed with a brain tumor after an MRI from a training day resulting in a crash. I learned that health isn't how much you weigh or how you look. It's what goes on internally and is influenced by what you consume.

Perspective Is Essential: I was faced with tremendous amounts of painful situations where people were shocked I continued to compete in BMX. But, I could always reframe my mindset into learning from my falls and refocusing on the vision.

Virtual Mentors: I saw @davemirralegacy on TV, and he inspired me to see what was possible if I wanted it. I looked up to him and others I admired in the sport & modeled their behaviors. This is what allowed me the opportunity to train, compete, and become friends with Dave and the others. 

Process > Outcomes. Bmx taught me the power of falling in love with the process, enjoying and focusing on the journey of achieving my goals.

Which resonates with you?

Authenticity can be a super power of ours.

When we decide & learn to utilize it. 

It’s no secret I get into a lot of deep content here, with my clients, & with anyone I come in contact with. 

I’ve learned that it’s a part of who I am. 

That part of me led me to my success in BMX as well as overcoming multiple brain tumors these last 12 years. 

It’s the part of me that can’t help but ask “how?” & “why?” things work the way they do. 

Other than those who know me really well, it may not be so obvious that I also have a goofy, weird, & silly side of my personality. 

It used to be present more when I was a kid into my teenager years. 

I’ve been digging into my past as well as my current psychology to make sense of how my current personality’s been conditioned over time. 

I’ve learned that I’ve had cameras on me since I was a teenager & that I’ve felt like I’ve had to hold back parts of my personality in an attempt to meet others expectations (fear or losing opportunities).

This lead to suppressing my self expression & led to a lot of issues when it came to a lot of communications & intimate relationships. 

👉🏼 was ashamed of self promotion (hurt sponsorship & partnership opportunities)
👉🏼 was afraid of expressing my true feelings (led to boundaries being walked over)
👉🏼 led to toxic, trauma bonded relationships held together by fear of being alone and beliefs of unworthiness 
👉🏼 created a sense of “stuck” & feeling unfulfilled 

I’m grateful to have done the uncomfortable work of exploring the depths of who I am, why I do what I do, & what I want to change about myself & life. 

I’m also thankful that pursuit led me to my calling in life as a coach & speaker today, as well as my loving, smart, & beautiful life partner @jlauricellaimages who took this photo 😆

The beautify of authenticity is that is always within us, we just may have to do some digging to reach it. 

It may not be fun or easy, but it’s worth the freedom on the other side. 

Happy Holidays. 

Josh P. 💚🧠✌️

There’s no wisdom at the moment of being triggered by external stimuli. 

When external stimuli trigger you, you can’t learn or act congruently to your desired outcomes. 

Your performance drops when you’re triggered, especially when it’s any form of stress: fear, anger, fatigue, etc.

Within 7ish minutes your IQ is split in about half, leading to bad decisions. 

Wisdom is neutral learning that can be shared & modeled for others. 

I like to think of wisdom as knowledge from experience without the emotional charge. 

The external world becomes less triggering when you can learn to stay neutral or get back to neutral. 

In doing so, we become more empowered to show up as our best selves, inspiring others to act similarly. 

The catch: it takes time to regulate self back to neutral to find those learnings & takes integrity to recognize those moments & take accountability for them. 

As you approach 2023, give yourself permission & time to:

👉🏼reflect on your 2022 experiences: the times you won, fell short, & acted in a way that did/didn’t serve your intentions in any area of life. 

👉🏼Forgive yourself & others for falling short, as hanging onto anger/shame/guilt hurts the self as described above.

🧐 Finally, ask yourself these 3 questions: 🧐

1. What did I experience that I didn’t necessarily want? 

2. What did I / can I learn from those experiences? 

3. How can those learnings serve me going forward in a holistic perspective regarding my personal & professional life? 

Josh P. 💚🧠✌️

Having seizures taught me the importance & power of our breath.

For the first time, 3 months ago, I was having a panic attack that was caused from disorientation going into the MRI tunnel. 

This happened again 2 weeks ago with another MRI. 

Each time brought on the thought “am I about to have a seizure?”

What helped me both times & lessened the amount of time I experienced the panic was focusing on my breath while counting 4 beats in & 6-8 beats out. 

I did this while touching each finger to my thumb on either hand to bring me back to my body. 

I’ve learned that our 🧠❤️ connection is powerful & is mostly responsible for our states of being. 

Our breath corresponds with our central nervous system (CNS) & when we focus on our breath, we can calm our stress response from whatever stimuli activated our CNS. 

When we are stressed, our breath gets quick & shallow; it is often present in our chest. 

When we are at peace, our breath gets deeper & slower: it is often present in our stomach. 

I remembered this both times & went all in with my focus on my breath. 

The affects took place quicker & shortened the panic response. 

Going in for another MRI next week, I feel confident as I’m prepared & competent with my breath work tool. 

Don’t sleep on the breath. It has the ability so reshape your life in so many ways. 

This is just one of the many forms it’s taking place in my life today. 

Josh P. 💚🧠✌️

“Active recovery day” routine for me is 🏌🏽

If you want to optimize your health & performance, you must prioritize your rest & recovery. 

Pushing yourself physically & mentally helps build up capacity & is required to grow. 

What we consume helps support that growth & refuel our physical energy.

Rest & recovery is the magic that brings the movement, mindset & nutrition pieces full circle. 

“Rest days” don’t mean you sit on the couch & do nothing, although those days are required every now & then.

Rest days are still an opportunity to move your body while not pushing it so it can stay fluid while fully recovering.

Thanks to my @whoop I can quantify my rest & recovery data to know when it’s time to pull back or when it’s “all systems go” to push hard that day. 

This is all part of the process I help lead my clients through as we create their roadmap for their ideal level of optimized performance. 

The main point: work hard, play hard, & recover well!

If you’ve read my recent updates this year regarding MRI’s, I experienced anxiety attacks the last 2 MRI’s for the first time in my life.

1. A positive & specifically stated desired outcome. 
2. Preparation (my breath work) built my competency which created my level of confidence today. 
3. Curiosity opener the door to new possibilities: I wondered WHAT IF I close my eyes during the entire MRI, which I’ve never done before. 

Well, that equation led to a successfully smooth MRI with no anxiety attacks. 

I’ll use this same formula tomorrow for my GK radiation treatment session, especially knowing I’ll be strapped down by my face to a bed going into the tunnel. 

I appreciate you all for the support and will do my best to get back to you all ASAP.

Sadly, we often wait for our health to become a problem before prioritizing it. 

What if you prioritized your health today?

What would that do for your energy & ability to improve other areas of your life? 

How would increasing your physical health & energy help you improve how you show up & perform within your:

👉🏼career?
👉🏼 relationship with your spouse, children, team member, or friends?
👉🏼 education?
👉🏼 freedom? 
👉🏼 leadership? 
👉🏼 finances?
👉🏼 hobbies?
👉🏼 creativity? 
👉🏼 sport?
👉🏼 art?

The list goes on. 

We as human beings have 4 layers of energy when it comes to performance:
1. Physical - the body. 
2. Mental - thoughts, beliefs, & goals. 
3. Emotional - feelings, community, & fulfillment.
4. Spiritual - purpose, values, & meaning. 

All 4 layers intertwine with one another & fuel one another. 

If one is layer neglected, the others start to deteriorate not far behind. 

What would 5% more energy, 5% less physical pain, or even 5% less baggage having to be lugged around free you up to do in your life?

Josh P. 💚🧠✌️

Your thinking you “don’t have time to exercise” is holding you back from higher performance. 

Not just in your career, but in all areas of life. 

It’s preventing you from showing up as your best self by lowering your ability to be fully present while easily triggered. 

Exercise is essential in:
👉🏼 Teaching your body how to handle the oscillations of daily stress. 
👉🏼 Conditioning your mind to embrace discomfort while growing your tolerance to external stimuli. 
👉🏼 Equipping your mental & emotional state to handle adversity out of your control. 
👉🏼 Building strength & endurance in all aspects of life. 
👉🏼 Improving overall 🧠 health, reliance, and performance. 

What’s equally important as exercise is REST. 

People who aren’t professional athletes are no different than an athlete who have rest days designed in their daily & weekly routines to recover properly. 

The only difference between a professional athlete & a parent, manger, executive, teacher, or artist is that an athletes job is to push their physical capacity during their training to levels others don’t regularly experience so they can perform as their best when the competition arises. 

This push also typically takes on a larger toll on their mental & emotional states of energy as the physical demand create that much more stress than non-athletes. 

The other difference is athletes DON’T “compete” nearly as much as a parent, manager or entrepreneur do. 

Non-athlete populations are “competing” 4-6 days a week, at least! 

That’s why it’s equally crucial to rest & reover properly. 

So you don’t:
1. Get injured 
2. Get tired & sick
3. Make poor decisions from lack of mental rejuvenation 

I have always traced my injuries back to a time where I didn’t recover enough in my competition days and had to learn the hard way. 

I was forced to chill. 

I now teach others how to design a optimal routine and lifestyle for their desired performance levels in all areas of life. 

Josh P. 💚🧠✌️

"A great deal of talent is lost to the world for want of a little courage. Every day sends to their graves insecure men whose timidity prevented them from making a first effort." 

The only thing standing in the way of our ideal life is ourselves. 

Specifically, our mind. 

It’s doing it’s job of protecting us from perceived harm by creating thoughts to sway us from action. 

Those thoughts elicit the emotion of fear and that emotion is what stops us from making the change or taking the first step. 

Then, we affirm our limiting beliefs or insecurities about ourselves further.

Fasting may help to lose weight in the short term, but it comes with a cost. 

The cost of added stress and muscle mass, which backfires the effort to fast.

And the weight lost is mostly water and glycogen (stored carbs in the muscle and liver).

Muscle mass is one of the most critical assets for metabolic health, thus an MVP for high performance. 

Fasting can be a great tool utilized every now and then, and for those with cancer or a lot of body fat to remove. 

But for about 99% of us who want to be metabolically fit and high performers, fasting can go against us. 

Here’s 1 critical reason why: skeletal muscle mass. 

Muscle is our largest “sink” for glucose, which increases insulin sensitivity and reduces the chances of food calories being stored as fat. 

Fasting deprives us of optimal muscle protein synthesis and the raw materials to do so, protein. 

The OMAD and IF camps are triggered, I know it. 

But, thanks to a process called gluconeogenesis, we can only utilize up to about 50g of protein at one serving.

The extra protein gets broken into glucose by the liver. 

And when we go long periods of time without eating, we reduce our protein intake and ability to maintain muscle mass. 

This becomes an integral part of optimal health and quality of life as we lose 3-8% muscle mass every decade once we get into our 30’s, which reduces our metabolic rate and we become less metabolically fit. 

When we become less metabolically fit:
- we lose energy
- we store more fat
- our cognitive performance lowers
- and we increase our risk for injury and disease. 

Fasting can be looked at as great mindset practice, but so can being intentional about protein consumption, sleep, and exercise. 

Protein > fasting!
